/* Case-local scaling minerals (ECLIPSES the standard catalogue -- taken
   whole). SNAPSHOT of data/standards/electrolyte/minerals.dat, restricted to
   {calcite, gypsum, halite}, the three this K(T) lesson contrasts.  Source:
   USGS PHREEQC phreeqc.dat (public domain), generated by
   bin/curate/parse_speciation.py.  The `analytic ( A1..A5 );` block is the
   PHREEQC -analytical_expression, used at runtime as an ANCHORED CORRECTION on
   logK25:  logK(T) = logK25 + [ana(T) - ana(298.15)]  (so logK(25 C) = logK25
   exactly).  `validC ( lo hi )` is the fitted validity range in Celsius (the
   run announces "K(T) extrapolated" outside it -- no silent extrapolation).

   THE LESSON lives in the SIGN of the K(T) slope:
     * calcite -- analytic, STRONGLY RETROGRADE: dissolution is exothermic, so
       its K(T) FALLS as T rises and SI_calcite RISES.  (Why hot heat-exchanger
       and RO concentrate surfaces scale with calcite.)
     * gypsum  -- analytic, mildly retrograde (solubility peaks near 40 C).
     * halite  -- NO analytic in phreeqc.dat (the db's -analytic line is
       commented out), so it falls back to constant-dH van't Hoff; dH > 0
       (endothermic) -> NORMAL solubility: K(T) rises, SI_halite drifts DOWN.
       The honest contrast: the calcite verdict flips with temperature while a
       normal-solubility salt does not. */

minerals
(
    { mineral calcite; formula "CaCO3"; masters ( { ion Ca; nu 1; } { ion HCO3; nu 1; } { ion H; nu -1; } );
      logK25 1.879; dH -28078.8; analytic ( 40.0171 -0.01928451 -5151.79 -8.66815 563713.9 ); validC ( 0 300 ); source "USGS PHREEQC phreeqc.dat (public domain); lit: 0 - 300 C, Ellis, 1959, Plummer and Busenberg, 1982"; }   // K(T) valid 0-300 C; HCO3-basis: CaCO3(s) + H+ = products
    { mineral gypsum; formula "CaSO4:2H2O"; masters ( { ion Ca; nu 1; } { ion SO4; nu 1; } ); nuWater 2;
      logK25 -4.55; dH -6700; analytic ( 72.244 -0.01474 -4040 -23.7823 ); source "USGS PHREEQC phreeqc.dat (public domain); lit: fits the appendix data of Appelo, 2015, AG 55, 62"; }
    { mineral halite; formula "NaCl"; masters ( { ion Na; nu 1; } { ion Cl; nu 1; } );
      logK25 1.57; dH 1370; source "USGS PHREEQC phreeqc.dat (public domain)"; }
);
